        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Down | Beckenham Kent</placeName>
                    <salute>Dear Sir,</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>My father directs me to thank you for the letter containing the details about the elephant case.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> If the story is true it appears to my father to be far more probable that the fruit contains some alkaloid such as that in indian hemp.<ref target="#foot.f2"/> This would equally well agree with the natives making a drink from it for similar cases are known e.g. the intoxicating (not alcoholic) liquor brewed from <hi rend="underline">agaricus muscarius</hi> by certain steppe tribes (Tartars I believe)<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
<p>Dear Sir | Yours faithfully | Francis Darwin <lb resp="#mjhawkins"/></p>
<p rend="left">Oct 29. 1877.</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
            
             
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-11214.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from W. M. Moorsom, 28 October 1877</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">In 1876, Vasily Preobrazhensky had asserted that the active principle of Indian hemp (<hi rend="italic">Cannabis sativa</hi>) was an alkaloid, which he identified as nicotine (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_10049.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Watt 1889–93</ref>, 2: 125).</note>
           <note xml:id="foot.f3"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_839.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">William Benjamin Carpenter</ref> had reported that the Tartars, who lived a nomadic life on the steppes of Russia, used the fly agaric (<hi rend="italic">Amanita muscaria</hi>, a synonym of <hi rend="italic">Agaricus muscarius</hi>) for the purposes of intoxication (Carpenter 1873, p. 316). The natives of Kamchatka in Russia were also famed for producing an inebriating liquor from <hi rend="italic">Agaricus muscarius</hi> (W. J. Hooker 1821, pt 2: 19).</note>
        </div>        
            
